{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"82b89de2-a6a3-441b-a414-0248d3a61097","content":"Use the `--filter` flag with `&` to combine conditions:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName~Integration & Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n- `~` means \"contains\"\n- `&` is logical AND\n\nThis assumes your Smoke tests are marked with `[Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]`. If you're using a custom `[CategoryAttribute]` or a different trait name, adjust accordingly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1ff7f4bf-2722-4c2d-8415-f6561b707405","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to construct a single combined filter expression for `dotnet test` that:\n1. Runs only tests with a \"Smoke\" category/trait\n2. From classes whose name contains \"Integration\"\n\nThey want this as a single `--filter` expression rather than separate flags.\n\nIn xUnit with `dotnet test`, the filter expression uses the `--filter` flag with MSTest/xUnit compatible filter syntax. The relevant properties are:\n\n- `FullyQualifiedName` or `ClassName` — to filter by class name\n- `Category` or `TestCategory` — for traits\n\nIn xUnit v3, traits like `[Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]` map to the `Category` filter property.\n\n\nThe combined filter uses the `~` operator for substring matching and `&` to combine conditions, so I can construct a single expression that filters for classes containing \"Integration\" and tests marked with the \"Smoke\" category.","outputTokens":338,"requestId":"E3C5:1ED62C:1728801:19F9B35:6A05262E"},"id":"031ec15d-dc42-49dc-83f2-c947a85c303b","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:32:38.413Z","parentId":"340f3f26-76e9-4ac5-afdc-d9422aca3778"}
